rish Brendan, Donal, Donovan, Fergal.","Irish (Monaghan): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Marcaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Marcach</i>’, a name meaning ‘horseman, knight’, from <i>marc</i> ‘horse’. Compare   Markham   2.","English: apparently from a placename meaning ‘boundary river’ in Old or Middle English, but no such place has been identified."]},{"name":"Markum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Markham  ."]},{"name":"Marcum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Markham  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Markham was born about 1264, in Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Sir John Markham, was 29 and his mother, Lady Clarissa de West, was 27. He had at least 2 sons with Sarah Switterton. He died about 1289, at the age of 27."},"et":{"about 1264–about 1289":"umbes 1264–umbes 1289","1264–1289":"1264–1289","–Male":"Surnud","1270–1295":"1270–1295","1290–1329":"1290–1329","1302–1302":"1302–1302","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1238–1276":"1238–1276","1238":"1238","1236":"1236",